I, uh, flew today.
First point of criticism: We need nicer flight logs. Black is boring, pink is not quite pink, but rather salmon-colored.
I wanted to fly since I was little.
And today it was like… I flew an airplane today. I haven't fully processed that yet.
Data from Flightaware.
I'm trying to go back next Saturday again. The weather doesn't look so good right now, but it's also only Monday.
It's already becoming clear where the problems lie. It will probably be VERY difficult to get medical permission because of the FAA's opinion on certain medications.
It's not impossible, but it will take VERY long and means a LOT of extra work.
That's certainly a bit disheartening, but it's still just another problem that you just have to solve. So far, it seems to be solvable. It just costs a lot of time and money.
If you want to know what's ahead of me.
The FAA is not a fan of ADHD. They will definitely not get a medical permission when taking medication against it.
https://youtu.be/W5JSfq6LLAU?si=xIxPaY8ayqqNSj4c
If I am able to choose my own tail number for an aircraft, you'll know it will definitely be a variant of N1337_, where _ represents the last available letter.
It's logical that the sun shines when I'm away, lol. Stupid cow.
I have to go back into the air. And the weather isn't playing along.
Welcome to sports flying 😜
I get the feeling that in the aviation industry, people tend to be more conservative, considering what kind of advertising YouTube has chosen for me, which videos are recommended to me, and what kind of comments are displayed to me.
If the weather plays along, I'll be flying again on Saturday.
I also found a pink logbook.
Have a nice Saturday morning. That's what I did today ^_^
#TeaganAir
It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe how it is, flying in a small plane, I would say it's a mix between a motorcycle/quad and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're immediately very fast. It's all a bit unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know it yet: You steer a plane on the ground with your feet, not with the control stick. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's no car.
In the air, it's wobbly, and you're sort of floating. It feels like you're in a boat on the water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes along and throws you off course, so you have to basically get used to the sea, just in the air.
One more random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs hurt, as if I had been to the gym.
This isn't like a Sunday drive in the car. It's more like a sport than a leisurely stroll, in my newfound opinion.
A lovely Saturday, my dear ones. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
I'm going there again tomorrow. Then we'll practice stall and slow flying.
The weather was turbulent today, but it was great fun. We practiced slow flying and stall. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph with a flight speed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit hazy higher up, but still nice.
FlightAware data track.
